{{short description|Etruscan combat helmet}}
{{refimprove|date=December 2010}}
[[File:Museum für Vor- und Frühgeschichte Berlin 010.jpg|thumb|right|250px|A '''Negau helmet''' excavated at [[Hallstatt Archaeological Site in Vače]], near [[Vače]], [[Slovenia]]. Kept by [[Museum für Vor- und Frühgeschichte (Berlin)|Museum of Prehistory and Early History (Berlin)]]]]

'''Negau helmet''' refers to one of 26 bronze [[helmet]]s (23 of which are preserved) dating to c. 450 BC–350 BC, found in 1812 in a cache in [[Ženjak]], near Negau, [[Duchy of Styria]] (now [[Negova]], [[Slovenia]]).<ref name="Smith2009">{{cite book|author=Jeremy J. Smith|title=Old English: A Linguistic Introduction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SduG-tIxL-AC&pg=PA125|date=2 April 2009|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-86677-4|pages=125–}}</ref> The helmets are of typical [[Etruscan civilization|Etruscan]] '[[vetulonic]]' shape, sometimes described as of the '''Negau type'''. They were buried in c. 50 BC, shortly before the [[Roman Empire|Roman]] invasion of the area. Helmets of the Negau type were typically worn by priests at the time of deposition of these helmets, so they seem to have been left at the Ženjak site for ceremonial reasons. The village of Ženjak was of great interest to German archaeologists during the [[Nazi]] period and was briefly renamed Harigast during [[World War II]]. The site has never been excavated properly.

==Inscriptions==
On one of the helmets ("Negau B"), there is an inscription in a [[Old Italic alphabet|northern Etruscan alphabet]]. The inscription need not date to c. 400 BC, but was possibly added by a later owner in c. 2nd century BC or later. It is read as:
<!--:<span dir=rtl >[[Image:EtruscanH-01.png|12px|H]][[Image:EtruscanA-01.png|12px|A]][[Image:EtruscanR-01.png|12px|R]][[Image:EtruscanI-01.png|12px|I]][[Image:EtruscanK-01.png|12px|G]][[Image:EtruscanA-01.png|12px|A]][[Image:EtruscanS-01.png|12px|S]][[Image:EtruscanT-01.png|12px|T]][[Image:EtruscanI-01.png|12px|I]][[Image:EtruscanT-01.png|12px|T]][[Image:EtruscanE-01.png|12px|E]][[Image:EtruscanI-01.png|12px|I]][[Image:EtruscanF-01.png|12px|V]][[Image:EtruscanA-01.png|12px|A]]///[[Image:EtruscanI-01.png|12px|I]][[Image:EtruscanP-01.png|12px|P]]</span>-->
:{{lang|gem|{{script/Old Italic|𐌇𐌀𐌓𐌉𐌊𐌀𐌔𐌕𐌉𐌕𐌄𐌉𐌅𐌀///𐌉𐌐|rtl=y}}}}
:''harikastiteiva\\\ip'',
Many interpretations of the inscription have been proffered in the past, but the most recent interpretation is by T.L. Markey (2001), who reads the inscription as 'Harigast the priest' (from *''[[teiwaz]]'' "god"), as another inscribed helmet also found at the site bears several names (mostly [[Celt]]ic) followed by religious titles.

In any case, the Germanic name ''Harigast'' is almost universally read. Formerly, some scholars have seen the inscription as an early incarnation of the [[runic alphabet]], but it is now accepted that the script is North Etruscan proper, and precedes the formation of the Runic alphabet. ''Harigast'' constitutes an attestation of the [[Germanic sound shift]], probably the earliest preserved, preceding [[Tacitus]] perhaps by some two centuries.<ref name="Smith2009"/>

Must (1957) reads ''Hariχas Titieva'' as a [[Raetic]] personal name, the first element from the Indo-European ([[Venetic]] rather than Germanic), the second from the [[Etruscan language|Etruscan]].

The four discrete inscriptions on the helmet usually called "Negau A" are read by Markey as: ''Dubni banuabi'' 'of Dubnos the pig-slayer'; ''sirago turbi'' 'astral priest of the troop'; ''Iars'e esvii'' 'Iarsus the divine'; and ''Kerup'', probably an abbreviation for a Celtic name like Cerubogios.

